    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="HHy5e2"&gt;An apparent “Juniper” Tesla Model Y was spotted under the veil in California, reigniting reports that the automaker is &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/3/1/23620672/tesla-model-y-is-getting-a-refresh"&gt;prepping a redesign&lt;/a&gt; of its popular electric SUV. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="S8rJHp"&gt;A new image was posted on Reddit showing a black Model Y with its front and rear bumpers covered up and, as &lt;a href="https://www.notateslaapp.com/news/2119/teslas-upcoming-model-y-project-juniper-spotted-with-front-bumper-camera-coming-in-2025"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Not a Tesla App&lt;/em&gt; reports&lt;/a&gt;, a front-mounted camera that should help with parking assistance since Tesla had &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2022/10/5/23388770/tesla-ultrasonic-sensors-uss-model-3-y-s-x-radar"&gt;removed ultrasonic sensors&lt;/a&gt; years ago.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="OPDwBC"&gt;The Model Y’s sedan counterpart, Model 3, received the refresh treatment in the US &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/1/10/24032562/tesla-model-3-2024-refresh-us-available-highland"&gt;at the beginning of this year&lt;/a&gt;, following a &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/9/1/23855176/tesla-new-model-3-design-highland"&gt;European debut&lt;/a&gt; in September. Tesla reworked the front and rear bumpers on the Model 3, gave it squinty headlights, added tines to the taillights, and switched to a spelled-out text logo. &lt;/p&gt;
